DESCRIPTION:<p><em>Operation Mincemeat</em> is the 2024 Olivier Award-winn
 ing Best New Musical \, the 2025 Tony Award&reg\; winner for Best Featured
  Actor in a Musical (Jak Malone)\, and was named the #1 Broadway Show of 2
 025 (<em>Entertainment Weekly</em>).<br /><br />The year is 1943 and right
  now we&rsquo\;re losing the war. Luckily\, we&rsquo\;re about to gamble a
 ll our futures on a stolen corpse. Bursting at the seams with the kind of 
 chaos you couldn&rsquo\;t invent\, the question is: how did a dead body\, 
 a fake love letter\, and-of all people-Ian Fleming come together to wrong-
 foot Hitler?<br /><br />&ldquo\;It's not just the best musical I&rsquo\;ve
  ever seen\; it&rsquo\;s the most rewarding theatrical experience I&rsquo\
 ;ve ever had.&rdquo\; - Taffy Brodesser-Akner\, <em>The New York Times Mag
 azine</em><br /><br />&ldquo\;The reviews have been ecstatic. The overwhel
 ming impression is of hopefulness\, possibility\, and joy.&rdquo\; &mdash\
 ; <em>The New York Times</em><br /><br />&ldquo\;The Brits have made the y
 ear&rsquo\;s funniest musical.&rdquo\; &mdash\; Peter Marks\, <em>The Wash
 ington Post</em><br /><br />&ldquo\;The best new song on Broadway&hellip\;
  that song will be sung for the next hundred years.&rdquo\; &mdash\; <em>V
 ulture</em><br /><br />&ldquo\;Part Mel Brooks\, part <em>SIX</em>\, part 
 <em>Hamilton</em> with a side order of <em>One Man\, Two Guvnors</em>.&rdq
 uo\; &mdash\; <em>The Daily Mirror</em><br /><br />&ldquo\;Too British? No
 t if you want to laugh uproariously &mdash\; and perhaps even unexpectedly
  shed a tear or two.&rdquo\; &mdash\; <em>Variety<br /><br /></em>&ldquo\;
 A laugh-out-loud delight\, with endless charm&hellip\; There&rsquo\;s noth
 ing else like it on Broadway.&rdquo\;  - <em>Entertainment Weekly</em></p>
LOCATION:Golden Theatre\, 252 West 45th Street\, New York NY 10036
END:VEVENT
